# functions 

# function using dickey fuller test to check for stationarity 
def fuller(
    array: np.array,
    critical = 0.05,
    stats=False) -> float:
    
    result = ts.adfuller(array, autolag='AIC') # lag chosen to minimize the information 
    p_val = result[1] 
    
    if(stats):
        print('ADF Statistics: %f' % result[0])
        print('P-value: %f' % p_val)
        print('Number of lags: %f' %result[2])
        print('Number of observations: %f' %result[3])
        print('Critical values:')
        for key, value in result[4].items():
            print('\t%s: %.3f' % (key, value))
    
    print('')
    if p_val <= critical: # if p value is less than 0.05 then data is stationary
        print('Reject null hypothesis(H0), data is stationary, good for model')
    else: # if p value is above 0.05 then datat is non-stationary (trending up)
        print('Accept null hypothesis(H0), data is non-stationary, bad for model')
        
        
        
        
# split train df and test df 
def train_test(df):
    
    train_df = df[:'2021-08-31'] # first 80%
    test_df = df['2021-09-01':] # last 20%
    train_per = round(len(train_df)/len(df) * 100,2)
    test_per = round(len(test_df)/len(df)*100,2)
    

    print('train_df: Shape:', train_df.shape, ',','percentage:',train_per,'%')
    print('test_df Shape:', test_df.shape,',','percentage:',test_per,'%')
    
    return train_df, test_df 
    
    



# grid search through data to find best AIC 
def best_aic(df):   
    
    # Define the p, d and q parameters to take any value between 0 and 2
    p = d = q = range(0, 2)
    
    # Generate all different combinations of p, q and q triplets
    pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))

    # Generate all different combinations of seasonal p, q and q triplets
    pdqs = [(x[0], x[1], x[2], 12) for x in list(itertools.product(p, d, q))]


    # Run a grid for best AIC value
    ans = []
    for i in pdq:
        for j in pdqs:
            try:
                mod = SARIMAX(df,
                                order=i,
                                seasonal_order=j)
                output = mod.fit(disp=False)
                ans.append([i, j, output.aic])
                print('ARIMA {} x {}12 : AIC Calculated ={}'.format(i, j, output.aic))

            except:
                continue
            
    # Find the parameters with minimal AIC value
    ans_df = pd.DataFrame(ans, columns=['pdq', 'pdqs', 'aic'])
    print('\nBest:',ans_df.loc[ans_df['aic'].idxmin()])
    return ans_df


# run the model with split data 
def fit_model (df, pdq=(1,0,1), pdqs=(0,0,0,1)):
    train_df, test_df = train_test(df)
    model = SARIMAX(train_df, order=pdq, seasonal_order=pdqs, enforce_stationarity=False,
                   enforce_invertibility=False)
    
    results = model.fit(disp=False)
    print(results.summary())
    results.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(14,10))
    plt.show()
    return train_df, test_df, results



        
    
        
def forecast_model(df, results, n):
    

    # perform forecast on the train_df and validate with test_df
    diff_forecast = results.get_forecast(steps=180)
    mean_forecast = diff_forecast.predicted_mean


    # confidence intervals of predictions 
    confidence_int = diff_forecast.conf_int()

    #lower and upper confidence limits 
    lower = confidence_int.loc[:, 'lower Revenue']
    upper = confidence_int.loc[:, 'upper Revenue']
    
    # plot forecasted revenue 
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.plot(df.index, df, label='Original Data')

    # mean predictions 
    plt.plot(mean_forecast.index, mean_forecast, color='r', label='Forecasted Data')

    # shade area between confidence 
    plt.fill_between(lower.index, lower, upper, color='pink', label='Confidence Levels')

    plt.title("Revenue with Forecast for 2022")
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Revenue, in millions')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.show()
    
    
# function to plot 2023 revenue 
def predict_2023(clean_results, non_results):
    
    # predicting stationary for 2023
    year_2023_pred = clean_results.get_prediction(start='2023-01-01', end = '2023-12-31', dynamic=True)
    # predicting non-stationary for 2023
    year_2023_pred_n = non_results.get_prediction(start='2023-01-01', end='2023-12-31', dynamic=True)
    
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    plt.plot(year_2023_pred.predicted_mean.index, year_2023_pred.predicted_mean, color='r', label='Stationary Prediction')
    plt.plot(year_2023_pred_n.predicted_mean.index, year_2023_pred_n.predicted_mean, color='b', label='Non-Stationary Prediction')
    plt.title('2023 Prediction')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Revenue, in millions')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()
    
    
    # revenue at end of 2023
    year_2023 = year_2023_pred.predicted_mean['2023-12-31']
    year_2023_n = year_2023_pred_n.predicted_mean['2023-12-31']
    
    # print revenue at end of 2023
    print(f'Stationary Revenue at end of 2023: {round(year_2023,2)} million')
    print(f'Non-Stationary Revenue at end of 2023: {round(year_2023_n,2)} million')

# visual functions 

# plot trend 
def plot_data(df):
    # line graph of revenue for 2 years 
    df.plot(figsize=(15,6))
    plt.ylabel('Revenue, in millions')
    plt.title('Revenue of Hospital Jan 2020- Dec 2021')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    

# plot rolling mean/std/original 
def plot_rolling_mean(df):
    
    # find rolling mean and standard deviation 
    rolling_mean = df.rolling(6).mean()
    rolling_std = df.rolling(6).std()
    
    #plot original/rolling mean/std 
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    plt.plot(df, color='lightblue', linewidth=6, label='Original Revenue')
    plt.plot(rolling_mean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean of Revenue')
    plt.plot(rolling_std, color='black', label='Rolling Standard of Revenue')
    plt.title('Revenue of Hospital over Last 6 Months')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    

# plot test/train 
def plot_test_train(train_df, test_df):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    plt.plot(train_df, color='black', label='Train Data')
    plt.plot(test_df, color='r', label='Test Data')
    plt.title("Train and Test Data")
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    

# method to plot spectral density of all data 

def sd_plot(data, target, ax, i: int, title: str) -> None:
    f, Pxx = signal.periodogram(data[target])
    ax[i].semilogy(f, Pxx, color='white')
    ax[i].fill_between(f, 0, Pxx, alpha=0.4)
    ax[i].set_title(title)
    ax[i].set_ylim([1e-4, 1e4])
    return None
